SIMPLE: exonerate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exonerate
<hw>Ex*on"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Exonerated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Exonerating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>exoneratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>exonerare</ets> to free from a
burden; <ets>ex</ets> out, from <ets>onerare</ets> to load,
<ets>onus</ets> load. See <er>Onerous</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
unload; to disburden; to discharge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>exonerate</qex> themselves into one common duct.</q>
<rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To relieve, in a moral sense, as of a charge,
obligation, or load of blame resting on one; to clear of something that
lies upon oppresses one, as an accusation or imputation; <as>as, to
<ex>exonerate</ex> one's self from blame, or from the charge of
avarice</as>.</def> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To discharge from duty or obligation, as a
bail.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To absolve; acquit; exculpate. See
<er>Absolve</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>exonerated</ent>⟦br⟧
